docs.abstract: The oil giant has put its plans for an initial public offering on hold, as it focuses on efforts to buy a stake in a Saudi chemical maker.
docs.snippet: The oil giant has put its plans for an initial public offering on hold, as it focuses on efforts to buy a stake in a Saudi chemical maker.
docs.lead_paragraph: Saudi Arabia’s state-owned oil giant has suspended its plans to go public, a decision that puts on hold what would have been by far the biggest initial offering on record — or perhaps signals its cancellation.

headline.main: Saudi Aramco Is Said to Postpone Its Potentially Record-Breaking I.P.O.
headline.print_headline: Saudi Oil Giant Suspends Plan To Go Public

byline.original: By Michael J. de la Merced and Clifford Krauss

docs.abstract: Ken Kurson, a friend of Jared Kushner’s and a past adviser to Donald J. Trump, withdrew from consideration for a prestigious position amid harassment allegations.
docs.snippet: Ken Kurson, a friend of Jared Kushner’s and a past adviser to Donald J. Trump, withdrew from consideration for a prestigious position amid harassment allegations.
docs.lead_paragraph: Ken Kurson is a confidant of Rudolph W. Giuliani. He is a onetime speechwriter for Donald J. Trump. And he is a close friend of Jared Kushner, Mr. Trump’s son-in-law, who appointed Mr. Kurson to run his weekly newspaper, The New York Observer.

headline.main: A Kushner Ally Was Up for a Federal Post. Then the F.B.I. Began Digging.

byline.original: By Jesse Drucker, Emily Steel and Danny Hakim

docs.abstract: Bankers have told Uber that its public offering could be worth $120 billion. That puts it in rare company with the likes of Facebook and Alibaba.
docs.snippet: Bankers have told Uber that its public offering could be worth $120 billion. That puts it in rare company with the likes of Facebook and Alibaba.
docs.lead_paragraph: Uber and Lyft have for years battled for customers in the fast-growing ride-hailing business. Now the bitter rivals may fight for investors in their initial public offerings.

headline.main: Uber and Lyft Charge Toward Potential I.P.O.s Next Year
headline.print_headline: I.P.O. Duel Is Looming For Uber And Lyft

byline.original: By Michael J. de la Merced and Kate Conger

docs.abstract: Tesla’s chief executive suggested that being a public company, beholden to shareholders, created perverse incentives for short-sellers.
docs.snippet: Tesla’s chief executive suggested that being a public company, beholden to shareholders, created perverse incentives for short-sellers.
docs.lead_paragraph: Elon Musk has become one of the world’s most prominent chief executives, and a billionaire several times over, by boldly making big bets on ideas that few others thought possible.

headline.main: Elon Musk Says Tesla May Go Private, and Its Stock Soars
headline.print_headline: Stock in Tesla Surges as Musk Floats Taking Carmaker Private

docs.abstract: The president said he wanted the Securities and Exchange Commission to weigh letting companies report results just twice a year.
docs.snippet: The president said he wanted the Securities and Exchange Commission to weigh letting companies report results just twice a year.
docs.lead_paragraph: President Trump asked the Securities and Exchange Commission to consider eliminating requirements that publicly traded companies post quarterly earnings reports, a move that could do away with a cornerstone of American capital markets.

headline.main: Trump Asks S.E.C. to Study Quarterly Earnings Requirements for Public Firms
headline.print_headline: Trump Wants S.E.C. Study  Of Quarterly Earnings

byline.original: By Michael J. de la Merced and Matt Phillips

docs.abstract: American companies are the largest source of demand for American stocks, and sharp tumbles have come when their buying slows.
docs.snippet: American companies are the largest source of demand for American stocks, and sharp tumbles have come when their buying slows.
docs.lead_paragraph: There are plenty of potential catalysts for the stock market sell-off that has swept through the markets this week. They include rising interest rates, growing tensions with China, expanding federal deficits and increasing regulatory risks for technology companies.

headline.main: The Biggest Buyers of American Stocks Are on the Sidelines Right Now
headline.print_headline: Buybacks Dip Could Factor Into Sell-Off

docs.abstract: The quarterly parade of updates on profits and losses will either give credence to fears about the economy or ease them.

docs.lead_paragraph: Last week was all about fear. This week, investors could turn to greed.

headline.print_headline: After Bad Week, Stock Investors  Look for Clues  In U.S. Earnings

docs.abstract: Sinking confidence in Rome’s solvency could cause financial chain reactions that would be difficult for governments and central banks to control.
docs.snippet: Sinking confidence in Rome’s solvency could cause financial chain reactions that would be difficult for governments and central banks to control.
docs.lead_paragraph: The European Union has sent the Italian budget back to Rome with a failing grade. Italian bonds are being pummeled in financial markets. Italy’s credit rating is perilously close to junk status.

headline.main: Italy Is in Trouble With the E.U. Here’s Why the World Should Care.
headline.print_headline: Why the World Should Care About Italy’s Debt Woes

docs.abstract: A surge in sales of the Model 3 helped lift the company’s performance, but big financial and production challenges remain.
docs.snippet: A surge in sales of the Model 3 helped lift the company’s performance, but big financial and production challenges remain.
docs.lead_paragraph: Tesla on Wednesday reported its first quarterly profit in two years and its biggest ever. But for the electric-car maker and its unpredictable chief, the question is whether it can keep making money.

headline.main: Tesla Reports a Rare Quarterly Profit, Its Biggest Ever
headline.print_headline: Tesla Reports a Rare Profit,  But Daunting Trials Remain

docs.abstract: You may never have heard of Bytedance or used any of its products. But chances are your teenager is already glued to the company’s music video app.
docs.snippet: You may never have heard of Bytedance or used any of its products. But chances are your teenager is already glued to the company’s music video app.
docs.lead_paragraph: BEIJING — A Chinese internet company that serves up homemade break-dancing videos, dishy news bites and goofy hashtag challenges has become one of the planet’s most richly valued start-ups, with a roughly $75 billion price tag. And it has big plans for storming phone screens across the rest of the globe, too.

headline.main: China’s King of Internet Fluff Wants to Conquer the World
headline.print_headline: The Chinese Internet Fluff King That’s Addicting Your Teenager
